  "prompt": "Why is Bogota cold?",
  "response": "Bogot\u00e1 is relatively cool due to several key factors:\n\n1. **Altitude**: The city is situated at a high elevation, approximately 2,640 meters (8,660 feet) above sea level. Higher altitudes generally result in cooler temperatures due to the thinner atmosphere and lower air pressure, which means less heat is retained.\n\n2. **Equatorial Location**: Although Bogot\u00e1 is located near the equator, its altitude mitigates the typical equatorial heat. The combination of high elevation and equatorial position means that while the city experiences fairly consistent year-round temperatures, these temperatures are cooler than those found at lower elevations in equatorial regions.\n\n3. **Climate**: Bogot\u00e1 has a subtropical highland climate (K\u00f6ppen climate classification Cfb), characterized by moderate temperatures throughout the year without extreme heat or cold. This climate typically results in pleasant but cool weather, with average temperatures ranging from around 8\u00b0C to 19\u00b0C (46\u00b0F to 66\u00b0F).\n\nThese factors contribute to Bogot\u00e1's unique climate, making it cooler than many other cities located near the equator.",
